snippet.textDisplay: I still use my 11inch 2011 MacBook Air. It’s great. It’s super light, I can throw it on my bed since it has an ssd, it doesn’t hardly get hot (I can work on 3 audacity files and a couple other things at the same time and still have it on my lap), LOVE the keys, and is perfectly fine for watching videos and writing essays. I bought it used in 2014 for $200 after the battery was replaced. Anyone who isn’t gaming or using heavy software like blender or davinchi should be perfectly fine with an Air. It’s not noticeably slow to the average person so it’s a great fit for most and I highly recommend buying a used or older model for kids and anyone on the go. Especially with airdrop (doesn’t work on macs before 2011 anymore). I can start a file on my phone or another Mac and drop it to the air and back whenever I need to.

snippet.textDisplay:
Linus' observation are true, within the context put forth... but those same observations are not as true over the passage of time. What do I mean? You take those same Windows machines in everyday use for two year, and a MacBook Air (or Pro, or any Mac) in use everyday over two years, and the results would be different. The Windows laptops performance degrade over that period, and the Mac machine do not seem to do so. I, myself, have experienced this, in every day use, as I have had Windows laptops (Samsung, Dell, and HP) and Apple laptops. The Windows laptops experience performance degradation over 1-2 year period -- becoming less snappy, longer to start, etc. Not so with the Mac (MacBook Air, MacBook Pro, and even desktop machines MacMini, and iMac). That's my experience... and it is consistent in my experience of typical everyday use.

Full disclosure, I am 33 year Mac aficionado having first bought a Mac SE back in the year 1987 (perhaps before the birth of Linus). In any event, I have to say that I thoroughly enjoy Linus' videos, and will keep watching them... they are entertaining, insightful and informative.

I am not an apple person, but I they do make better lasting laptops. I know people still using a 2012 MacBook Pro. My windows laptop has had so many driver and power issues it renders it almost useless. Kernel Panics, a thunderbolt port that doesn't work reliably and hard freezes the system when moving big files, randomly disconnecting drives and overheating terribly... MacBooks last a long time.

After two terrible Dell Laptops, I will be going back to a MacBook Pro for my next laptop.

snippet.textDisplay: I have that same Macbook air, i got it back in 2017 for university, i'm usually pretty anti-apple but i needed a small laptop with good battery and low maintenance, it was either that or the Dell and since i've found the macbook with a huge discount (it was like 750e instead of 1,2k) i went with it, the building quality is definitely better than any laptop i've had, especially Acer's, but my god the screen is horrible, i don't need a good display because i just use this machine to code for school but having a non-FullHD on a machine that is sold at 1,2k retail price is fucking atrocious, overall i don't regret buying this but it does have a lot of issues, it overheats with streaming/netflix, has very low storage space and its CPU power is awful, but tbh for what i need it at that price there was nothing else, it's very portable, keyboard feels better than any other laptop in that price range and the trackpad is great, overall im still not a big fan of MacOS though

snippet.textDisplay: I work for a tech company .. one of my metrics to track is why people select what they do.  The reason people chose the Mac over the PCs was their kids.  People I know you love your kids and they are smart young people but looking at specs on a computers they seriously have no ideal what they are looking at .. The Mac doesn’t fare well unless you make a unique excuse.. like for coding .. well it shows more lines ...  great until you run across a code it can’t be used for and you will rendering it a paper weight.  I have had people chose a 16gb i7 MacBook Pro over a 64gb i7 Lenovo  that was lighter, had touch screen and better in every way because their kid said it was a better machine.  They would be doing coding but looking at huge files where ram was needed and users never seem to like closing tabs on their browsers.. that is when a person needs RAM.  Ugh..Lenovo easy choice except when you have kids over your shoulder.
